## [1] "projecttemplate.html" "projecttemplate.rmd"  "tidy-data.pdf"       
## [4] "wineQualityInfo.txt"  "wineQualityReds.csv"

The dataset is related to red variants of the Portuguese Vinho Verde wine. The inputs include objective tests (e.g.PH values) and the output is based on sensory data (median of at least 3 evaluations made by wine experts). Each expert graded the wine quality between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent). Only physicochemical (inputs) and sensory (the output) variables are available.

I will explore the wine quality and physicochemical properties of these wines. I want to know how the chemical properties influence the quality of red wines.

There are 1599 observations of 13 numeric variables. X appears to be the unique identifier. quality is an ordered, categorical, discrete variable. From the literature, this was on a 0-10 scale, and was rated by at least 3 wine experts. The values ranged only from 3 to 8, with a mean of 5.6 and median of 6. All other variables seem to be continuous quantities (w/ the exception of the .sulfur.dioxide suffixes). From the variable descriptions, it appears that
fixed.acidity ~ volatile.acidity and
free.sulfur.dioxide ~ total.sulfur.dioxide may possibly be
dependent, subsets of each other.

get_bivariate_boxplot <- function(x, y, ylab) {
  return(ggplot(data = wine, aes(x = x, y = y)) + geom_boxplot() + ylab(ylab))
}

grid.arrange(get_bivariate_boxplot(wine$quality, wine$fixed.acidity,
                                   'fixed acidity'),

The above box plots show that a good wine has the following features:
* higher fixed acidity & citric acid * lower volatile acidity * lower pH * higher sulphates * higher alcohol

Lets dig into these features a little more

ggplot(data=wine, aes(x=quality, y=fixed.acidity)) +
  geom_boxplot()

There seems to be very little relation between the quality and
fixed.acidity.

ggplot(data=wine, aes(x=quality, y=citric.acid)) +
  geom_boxplot()

citric.acid seems to have a strong effect on quality. Quality increases
with the increase in citric.acid.

ggplot(data=wine, aes(x=quality, y=volatile.acidity)) +
  geom_boxplot()

volatile.acidity also has a strong effect (negative correlation) on quality.
Quality decreases with the increase in citric.acid.

#  Alcohol level
ggplot(data=wine, aes(y=alcohol, x=quality)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

We can clearly see the correlation here. As the alcohol level increases
quality of wine increases with it. But as there are a lot of outliers, lets
try using a simple linear model to check the connection.

alcoholQual <- lm(as.numeric(quality) ~ alcohol, data = wine)
summary(alcoholQual)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = as.numeric(quality) ~ alcohol, data = wine)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -2.8442 -0.4112 -0.1690  0.5166  2.5888 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) -0.12503    0.17471  -0.716    0.474    
## alcohol      0.36084    0.01668  21.639   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.7104 on 1597 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2267, Adjusted R-squared:  0.2263 
## F-statistic: 468.3 on 1 and 1597 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
alcoholDF = data.frame(wine$quality )
alcoholDF$predictions <- predict(alcoholQual, wine)
alcoholDF$error <- (alcoholDF$predictions - as.numeric(wine$quality))/as.numeric(wine$quality)

ggplot(data=alcoholDF, aes(x=wine.quality, y=error)) +
  geom_boxplot()

We get an R-squared value of 0.2263. Which is not enough by itself. Lets
look at other variables to generate a better model.

 citric.acid and volatile.acidity have a strong effect on the quality.
